1package Perlscan;
2## ABSTRACT:  Lexical analysis module for Perl -- parses one line of Perl program (which should contain a complete statement) into tokens/lexems
3##          For alpha-testers only. Should be used with Pythoinizer testing suit
4##
5## Copyright Nikolai Bezroukov, 2019-2020.
6## Licensed under Perl Artistic license
7##
8## REQURES
9##        pythonizer.pl
10##        Pythonizer.pm
11##        Softpano.pm
12
13#--- Development History
14#
15# Ver      Date        Who        Modification
16# ====  ==========  ========  ==============================================================
17# 0.10 2019/10/09  BEZROUN   Initial implementation
18# 0.20 2019/11/13  BEZROUN   Tail comment is now treated as a special case and does not produce a lexem
19# 0.30 2019/11/14  BEZROUN   Parsing of literals completly reorganized.
20# 0.40 2019/11/14  BEZROUN   For now double quoted string are translatied into concatenation of components
21# 0.50 2019/11/15  BEZROUN   Better parsing of Perl literals implemented
22# 0.51 2019/11/19  BEZROUN   Problem of translation of ` ` (and rx() is that it is Python version dependent
23# 0.52 2019/11/20  BEZROUN   Problem of translation of tr/abc/def/ solved
24# 0.53 2019/12/20  BEZROUN   Here strings are now processed
25# 0.60 2020/02/03  BEZROUN   Allow processing multiline statements
26# 0.61 2020/02/03  BEZROUN   If the line does not ends with ; ){ or } we assume that the statement is continued on the next line
27# 0.62 2020/05/16  BEZROUN   Nesting is performed from this module
28# 0.63 2020/06/15  BEZROUN   Tail comments are artifically made properties of the last token in the line
29# 0.64 2020/08/06  BEZROUN   gen_statement moved from pythonizer, ValCom became a local array
30# 0.65 2020/08/08  BEZROUN   Diamond operator (<> <HANDLE>) is treated now as identifier
31# 0.66 2020/08/09  BEZROUN   gen_chunk moved to Perlscan module. Pythoncode array made local
32# 0.70 2020/08/10  BEZROUN   Postfix statements accomodated
33# 0.71 2020/08/11  BEZROUN   scanning of regular expressions improved. / qr and 'm' are treated uniformly
34# 0.72 2020/08/12  BEZROUN   Perl_default_var is renamed to default_var
35# 0.73 2020/08/14  BEZROUN   Decoding of system variables in double quoted literals implemented
36# 0.74 2020/08/18  BEZROUN   f-strings are generated for double quoted literals for Python 3.8
37# 0.75 2020/08/25  BEZROUN   variable for other namespaces are recognized now
38# 0.76 2020/08/27  BEZROUN   Special subroutine for putting regex in quote created
39# 0.80 2020/08/31  BEZROUN   Handling of regex improved, keywords are added,
40# 0.81 2020/08/31  BEZROUN   Handling of % improved.
41# 0.82 2020/09/01  BEZROUN   my is eliminated, unless is the first token (for my $i...)
42# 0.83 2020/09/02  BEZROUN   if regex contains both single and double quotes use """. Same for tranlation of double quoted
43# 0.90 2020/09/17  BEZROUN   Adapted for detection of global identifiers.
44# 0.91 2020/09/18  BEZROUN   ValType array added and now used in pass 0: values set to 'X' for special variables
45# 0.92 2020/10/12  BEZROUN   Better special var handling. Many bug fixes
46# 0.93 2021/11/21  SNOOPYJC  See specific changes in main module

158   # issue s40:
159   # From the documentation: If the condition expression of a while statement is
160   # based on any of a group of iterative expression types then it gets some magic
161   # treatment. The affected iterative expression types are readline, the <FILEHANDLE>
162   # input operator, readdir, glob, the <PATTERN> globbing operator, and each. If the
163   # condition expression is one of these expression types, then the value yielded by
164   # the iterative operator will be implicitly assigned to $_. If the condition
165   # expression is one of these expression types or an explicit assignment of one of
166   # them to a scalar, then the condition actually tests for definedness of the
167   # expression's value, not for its regular truth value.                     
168   %WHILE_MAGIC_FUNCTIONS=('glob'=>1, 'readline'=>1, 'readdir'=>1,
169                          # this one causes problems: 'each'=>1,

307       #
308       # TOKENS TYPES:
309       # a => Array like @arr
310       # b
311       # c => Control like if, for, foreach, while, unless, until, ...
312       # d => Digits like 123 or 12.34 or .5
313       # e
314       # f => Built-in function like abs, atan2, basename, or chomp
315       # g => Glob like <*.c>
316       # h => Hashname like %hash
317       # i => BareWord like ABC or abc - could be a local sub name
318       # j => Diamond like <> or <$fh> or <FH>
319       # k => Special control like last, next, return, or sub
320       # l, m,
321       # n => not
322       # o => or, and, xor - lower precedence than || &&
323       # p
324       # q => Pattern like  m/.../, s/../.../, tr/../../, or wr, or /.../
325       # r => range (..)
326       # s => Scalar like $var
327       # t => Variable type like local, my, own, state
328       # u, v, w
329       # x => Executable in `...` or qx
330       # y => Extra python code we need to generate as is (used in multi_subscripts)
331       # z
332       # A => => (arrow)
333       # C => More control like default, else, elsif
334       # D => -> (dot in python)
335       # F => Named Unary Operators (not generated, but used in calls to next_lower_or_equal_precedent_token)
336       # G => TypeGlob *name
337       # H => Here doc <<
338       # I => >>
339       # P => :: (package reference)
340       # W => Context manager (with)
341       # 0 => &&, ||
342       # ^ => ++ or --
343       # > => comparison like > < >= <= == eq ne lt gt le ge
344       # = => assignment like = += -= etc
345       # ? => ? (part of ? : )
346       # : => : or =>
347       # . => . or -> or ::
348       # * => *, **, or x
349       # ! => !
350       # +, -, /, % => Operators
351       # ~ => Pattern match like =~ or !~
352       # " => Quoted string or q/abc/, qq(def), etc

5543sub escape_backslash
5544# All special symbols different from the delimiter and \ should be escaped when translating Perl single quoted literal to Python
5545# For example \n \t \r  are not treated as special symbols in single quotes in Perl (which is probably a mistake)
5546#
5547# Perl: A backslash represents a backslash unless followed by the delimiter or another backslash, in which case the delimiter or backslash is interpolated.
5548#
5549# Python: all unrecognized escape sequences are left in the string unchanged, i.e., the backslash is left in the result.
5550# Recognized in Python:
5551# \newline Backslash and newline ignored
5552# \\ Backslash (\)
5553# \' Single quote (')
5554# \" Double quote (")
5555# \a ASCII Bell (BEL)
5556# \b ASCII Backspace (BS)
5557# \f ASCII Formfeed (FF)
5558# \n ASCII Linefeed (LF)
5559# \r ASCII Carriage Return (CR)
5560# \t ASCII Horizontal Tab (TAB)
5561# \v ASCII Vertical Tab (VT)
5562# \ooo Character with octal value ooo
5563# \xhh Character with hex value hh
5564# \N{name} Character named name in the Unicode database
5565# \uxxxx Character with 16-bit hex value xxxx
5566# \Uxxxxxxxx Character with 32-bit hex value xxxxxxxx

sub optimize_list_of_n                                          # SNOOPYJC
# See if we can optimize out this _list_of_n call
{
    my $line = shift;   # Line of python code
    my $pos = shift;    # Points to start of "list_of_n("

    return $line if in_string($line, $pos);
    my $open = $pos + length('list_of_n');        # Point to '('
    return $line if substr($line, $open+1, 1) ne '(';    # We must have list_of_n((...), N)
    my $close = python_matching_paren($line, $open);
    return $line if $close < 0;
    my $tuple_start = $open+1;
    my $tuple_end = python_matching_paren($line, $tuple_start);
    return $line if $tuple_end < 0;
    return $line if substr($line, $tuple_end+1, 2) ne ', ';
    my $count = substr($line, $tuple_end+3, ($close-($tuple_end+3)));
    return $line if $count !~ /\d+/;
    # LOL it's never that easy:
    #my $commas = substr($line, $tuple_start, ($tuple_end+1-$tuple_start)) =~ tr/,//;
    my $tuple_contents = substr($line, $tuple_start+1, ($tuple_end-1-$tuple_start));
    $tuple_contents = &Pythonizer::eat_strings($tuple_contents);
    my $commas = 0;
    for(my $i = 0; $i < length($tuple_contents); $i++) {
        my $ch = substr($tuple_contents,$i,1);
        if($ch eq '(') {
            my $end = python_matching_paren($tuple_contents, $i);
            return $line if($end < 0);
            $i = $end;
        } elsif($ch eq ',') {
            $commas++;
        }
    }
    return $line if $count != ($commas+1);

    if(substr($line, $pos-1, 1) eq '_') {       # _list_of_n
        $pos--;
    } elsif(substr($line, $pos-(length($PERLLIB)+1), length($PERLLIB)+1) eq "$PERLLIB.") {
        $pos -= (length($PERLLIB)+1);
    }
    # remove the list_of_n call and just leave the prefix, the tuple, and the suffix
    return substr($line, 0, $pos-1) . substr($line, $tuple_start, ($tuple_end+1-$tuple_start)) . substr($line, $close+1);
}

sub get_pythonizer_options_used
# Try to get the options used when pythonizing the given file
{
    local $.;

    my $pyfile = shift;

    my $python_file;

    if(!open(PYTHON, '<', $pyfile)) {
        return undef;
    }
    my $l1 = <PYTHON>;          #!/usr/bin/env python3
    my $l2 = <PYTHON>;          # Generated by "pythonizer ddts_archivalScript.pl" v0.964 run by JO2742 on Mon Mar 14 00:21:50 2022
                                # Generated by "pythonizer -M -v0 main.pl" v0.964 run by JO2742 on Sun Mar 13 22:55:12 2022
    close(PYTHON);
    my $result = '';
    if($l2 =~ /^# Generated by ".*? (-.*)? [A-Za-z0-9_\/\\.]+" v/) {
        $result = $1;
    }
    say STDERR "get_pythonizer_options_used($pyfile) = $result" if $::debug;
    return $result;
}

sub compute_desired_use_require_options
# For each lib that we use/require, compute the desired options needed to translate it properly, considering
# name mapping issues.  The '-R' flag options is what we are computing here.
{
    return if(scalar(%UseRequireVars) == 0);    # Don't do anything if we have no vars to take care of
    
    # start by looking at all names in our NameMap, and see which ones have multiple sigils at the "package" level, and add
    # them into another entry to UseRequireVars using '.' as the filename to represent the file being currently processed
    my %ournames = ();
    for my $name (keys %NameMap) {
        my @sigils = keys %{$NameMap{$name}};
        next if scalar(@sigils) == 1;
        my $found_package_var = 0;
    SIGILLOOP:
        for my $sigil (@sigils) {
            for my $sub (keys %sub_varclasses) {
                my $fullname = $sigil . $name;
                if(exists $sub_varclasses{$sub}->{$fullname} && $sub_varclasses{$sub}->{$fullname} eq 'package') {
                    $found_package_var = 1;
                    last SIGILLOOP;
                }
            }
        }
        if($found_package_var) {
            my $pkg = cur_package() . '::';
            for my $sigil (@sigils) {
                $ournames{$sigil . $pkg . $name} = 1;
            }
        }
    }
    $UseRequireVars{'.'} = \%ournames;

    # Now walk thru UseRequireVars and pick out the ones with multiple sigils, these have to have the -R option passed to the
    # modules that reference them
    
    my %names_to_sigils=();             # Map from names with packages but w/o sigils to the sigils referenced
    for my $file (keys %UseRequireVars) {
        for my $fullname (keys %{$UseRequireVars{$file}}) {
            my $sigil = substr($fullname,0,1);
            my $name = substr($fullname,1);
            if($sigil =~ /\w/) {        # No sigil
                $sigil = '';
                $name = $fullname;
            }
            $names_to_sigils{$name}{$sigil} = 1;
        }
    }

    # Now compute which files need which -R options based on which names they refer to

    for my $name (sort keys %names_to_sigils) {      # like $main::name - we sort them so we don't have to worry about matching -Rabc,def with -Rdef,abc
        my @sigils = keys %{$names_to_sigils{$name}};
        next if(scalar(@sigils) == 1);
        for my $file (keys %UseRequireVars) {
            $needs_R = 0;
            for my $sigil (@sigils) {
                if(exists $UseRequireVars{$file}{$sigil . $name}) {
                    $needs_R = 1;
                    last;
                }
            }
            if($needs_R) {
                my $basename = $name =~ s/[\w:]+::(\w+)$/$1/r;
                if(exists($UseRequireOptionsDesired{$file})) {
                    $UseRequireOptionsDesired{$file} .= ',' . $basename;
                } else {
                    $UseRequireOptionsDesired{$file} = '-R' . $basename;
                }
                if($file eq '.') {              # if we're setting for us, then handle that immediately here
                    remap_conflicting_names($basename, '', '');
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
=cut
